        Chart Review 12/07/24

        Oh hi! Didn't see you there! Are you ready for some WACKY (imagine the word but with some echo effects), BONKERS (same here), and downright MAD (you get the joke right?) chart stories?

        You do? Oh good, thanks for asking.

        You know that film Groundhog Day? Where a man keeps experiencing the same day, over and over again, and desperately tries to find a way to break the cycle? Yeah, turns out the Top 10 has ended up as boring as it always has. So yet again, it's time to clutch at straws and gawk at any so-called 'movement' the upper end of the best-sellers delivers us.

        Like the new No.1. Which is actually an old one.

        Yeah, turns out Sabrina Carpenter loves the top spot, who knew. It's not like you'd have noticed on Spotify or anything. After 3 weeks of serving us massive helpings of Please Please Please, she's now taken it OLD SKOOL and forced Espresso to have another 7 days at the summit, after the 5 times it was stranded at No.1 back in April and May. I can only imagine the madness that happens when her album arrives in August. It can't be any worse than seeing you-know-who hog the top spot for the rest of the summer.

        Speaking of which, Taylor Swift has been kicked off the album chart top spot. Again. That means the Milky Bars are on Leicester's finest lad-impressers, Kasabian, who now have a 7th best-seller in the form of Happenings to gloat at us with, and pelt us with their Oasis for Northface shtick. Although, having said that, reviews for this thing have officially deemed them as "Coldplay but slightly more cool". Which is probably the most depressingly funny thing I've seen in an album review all year. I mean, come on, the only way you could do worse is if you WERE Coldplay.

        OH WAIT.

        Anyways, that's it for the upper half, apart from the return to the Top 10 for one of the more surprising hits of the past few months. You know, apart from All The Stars and that one Maroon 5 song he was one that no one liked, Kendrick Lamar hasn't been one to stick around in the charts for very long, has he? The likes of HUMBLE., i, and Die Hard all vanished as quickly as my dignity, and you probably attach that stigma to Not Like Us after all that Drake rivalry drama died down, as it casually sunk away from its No.6 peak in the chart. At least that was until he did a West Coast gig recently, and it involved him performing this song so many times I'm pretty sure he's still there whipping Twitter into a frenzy. Combine that with the release of a video last Friday that may as well be his victory parade around the streets with how many references it makes, and now Not Like Us has swung up to No.9 this week off the back of this. All that's left to say here is this. .

        Also, Three Lions is back at 20, but we can save that speech for next week when the Euros are done and England end up frauding their way to victory. Unfortunately. Neil Diamond and Fat Les have also re-entered, so expect some mad shenanigans next time we chat.

        There are new hits to dig through though, so we might as well get them out the way. You know Eminem, right? Decent little rapper, chart presence for a quarter of a century, former Slim Shady. Key word is FORMER, because new album The Death of Slim Shady is out today, and you can probably guess why it's called that. Last Wednesday, Marshall Mathers slapped out a song called TOBEY with Big Sean and BabyTron, and just kinda hoped for the best. Turns out 78 was it's best last time out, but now it has shot up to 29 with little difficulty, and it could probably do some stuff next week as well. Just a shame it goes on forever and doesn't excite me in the slightest. Maybe next time out, eh?

        Three places below him is a guy that invokes memories of 2017 like no other, Ed She- nah only kidding. Quavo, a man who went from a member of Migos to LITERALLY EVERY TRANSATLANTIC SMASH that year and back again without anyone noticing.I'm The One, Strip That Down, Congratulations, Know No Better. He was on all of them, you couldn't escape him. Odd to think that he's never had a solo Top 100 single on these shores, nevermind a Top 40 success, but that changes now with Tough debuting at 32. Admittedly, that may have something to do with the fact that it features a certain Lana Del Rey, who with A&W (shouldn't have peaked at 41) last year showed that she CAN and WILL do rap without embarrassing everybody involved. Having said that though, as of the time I'm writing this, I had never Tough until the chart show today, so my feelings remain muted. Let's just agree to disagree to this song is just average, I don't know where the hype comes from. Pink Skies by Zach Bryan returns as well, thanks to his album not doing as well as you'd think he would. 16's a little disappointing for him, don't you think? I am still unimpressed as I was when it first charted, sadly.

        Outside the Top 40 and we have a new one at 56 from, erm.. LeoStayTrill and Mr Reload It with Pink Lemonade (Str8 Reload).
